## Inventory Structure

DebOps uses Ansible inventory files organized as a directory tree. The layout
shown below is a common convention created by the ``debops project init``
command, but inventory can also be defined in ``.yml`` / ``.yaml`` files or be
entirely dynamic. Always check the actual project layout rather than assuming
a fixed structure.

Load the ``debops-add-host`` skill for the full workflow to add a new host.
Load the ``debops-enable-service`` skill to enable a service role.

### Project layout

**Legacy project**::

    ansible/inventory/
    ├── hosts
    ├── group_vars/
    │   └── all/
    │       └── keyring.yml
    └── host_vars/

**Modern project** (with views)::

    ansible/views/<view>/inventory/
    ├── hosts
    ├── group_vars/
    │   └── all/
    │       └── keyring.yml
    └── host_vars/

In modern projects, each "view" has its own inventory. Find the view
name by checking ``.debops/conf.d/view-*.yml``.

### Host groups

**``[debops_all_hosts]``** - Required base group. Every managed host must
be listed here (or be a child of this group):

```ini
[debops_all_hosts]
hostname    ansible_host=hostname.example.com
```

**``[debops_service_<name>]``** - Enable a DebOps service role on a host:

```ini
[debops_service_nginx]
hostname
```

**``[debops_service_<name>:children]``** - Apply a service role to all
hosts in another group without listing them individually:

```ini
[debops_service_sssd:children]
debops_all_hosts
```

**Custom groups** - Define your own group names for organizational
purposes, then attach them to ``[debops_all_hosts:children]``:

```ini
[debops_all_hosts:children]
webservers
databases

[webservers]
web01

[databases]
db01
```

Hosts in a ``:children`` group inherit all service roles from the parent.

### Host naming

Hostnames should match the Ansible hostname used in playbooks. Use
``ansible_host=`` to set the connection address separately:

```ini
hostname    ansible_host=fqdn.example.com
```

For the Ansible Controller itself, use ``ansible_connection=local``.

Range patterns are supported for bulk additions:

```ini
[debops_all_hosts]
web[01:50]    ansible_host=web<01:50>.example.com
```

### Variables

Variables are stored in YAML files under ``group_vars/`` and
``host_vars/``. Global variables that apply to all hosts go in
``group_vars/all/``, organized by role prefix:

```
group_vars/all/
├── nginx.yml
├── postfix.yml
├── sshd.yml
└── ...
```

Variables use the role name as a prefix:

```yaml
# group_vars/all/nginx.yml
nginx_flavor: 'full'
nginx__deploy_state: 'present'
```

Per-host overrides go in ``host_vars/<hostname>/``:

```yaml
# host_vars/web01/nginx.yml
nginx_flavor: 'passenger'
```

Load the ``debops-find-documentation`` skill to look up available
role variables and their defaults.

### Inspecting the current inventory

Read the ``hosts`` file directly to see all groups and members. Read
``group_vars/`` and ``host_vars/`` to see current variable
configuration. Use ``debops run tools/debug -l <hostname>`` to dump
all collected variables for a specific host.

### Removing entries

To decommission a host, remove it from all sections in the ``hosts``
file. To disable a service for a host, remove it from the
``[debops_service_<name>]`` section.

### Safety

Always use ``debops check`` (dry-run with diff) before applying
inventory changes. Only use ``debops run`` when the user explicitly
confirms.
